{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RpQR26CQvek7mmzqjvHn28","type":"tool_result","content":"     1в†’---\n     2в†’stepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4]\n     3в†’inputDocuments:\n     4в†’  - _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/tech-spec-rust-stack-support.md\n     5в†’  - _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd-operational-excellence.md\n     6в†’  - _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-operational-excellence.md\n     7в†’---\n     8в†’\n     9в†’# Rust Stack Support - Epic Breakdown\n    10в†’\n    11в†’## Overview\n    12в†’\n    13в†’This document provides the complete epic and story breakdown for adding full Rust stack support to codeharness at parity with Node.js and Python.\n    14в†’\n    15в†’## Requirements Inventory\n    16в†’\n    17в†’### Functional Requirements\n    18в†’\n    19в†’FR1: System detects Rust projects via `Cargo.toml` presence and returns stack `'rust'`\n    20в†’FR2: System detects Rust app type (CLI, server, library, agent, generic) by parsing `Cargo.toml` sections and dependencies\n    21в†’FR3: System detects `[workspace]` projects and treats them as single projects with `--workspace` flags\n    22в†’FR4: System generates multi-stage Dockerfile for Rust projects (build + runtime stages)\n    23в†’FR5: System installs OTLP crates (`opentelemetry`, `opentelemetry-otlp`, `tracing-opentelemetry`, `tracing-subscriber`) via `cargo add`\n    24в†’FR6: System provides LLM guidance doc for Rust OTLP instrumentation (`templates/otlp/rust.md`)\n    25в†’FR7: System detects `cargo-tarpaulin` as coverage tool for Rust projects\n    26в†’FR8: System parses `tarpaulin-report.json` for coverage percentage\n    27в†’FR9: System parses `cargo test` output for pass/fail counts\n    28в†’FR10: System generates AGENTS.md with Rust build/test commands\n    29в†’FR11: System creates Semgrep rules for Rust observability patterns (`tracing` crate)\n    30в†’FR12: System creates verification Dockerfile for Rust projects\n    31в†’FR13: System registers `cargo-tarpaulin` in dependency registry\n    32в†’FR14: System expands state types to support Rust coverage tool and OTLP config\n    33в†’\n    34в†’### NonFunctional Requirements\n    35в†’\n    36в†’NFR1: No file exceeds 300 lines (existing constraint from architecture)\n    37в†’NFR2: All new code has unit tests вЂ” 0 regressions on existing tests\n    38в†’NFR3: No new npm dependencies added to codeharness itself\n    39в†’NFR4: Cargo.toml parsing uses simple string matching вЂ” no TOML parser dependency\n    40в†’NFR5: All changes follow existing Result<T> pattern and module boundaries\n    41в†’\n    42в†’### Additional Requirements\n    43в†’\n    44в†’- Workspace detection must not break single-crate projects (false positive guard)\n    45в†’- `cargo-tarpaulin` is runtime-only dependency вЂ” not required at codeharness build time\n    46в†’- Semgrep Rust rules target standard `tracing` crate patterns only (custom macros out of scope)\n    47в†’- Verification Dockerfile needs Python for Semgrep even in Rust projects\n    48в†’\n    49в†’### FR Coverage Map\n    50в†’\n    51в†’| FR | Epic | Story |\n    52в†’|----|------|-------|\n    53в†’| FR1, FR2, FR3 | Epic 1 | 8-1 |\n    54в†’| FR14 | Epic 1 | 8-2 |\n    55в†’| FR7, FR8, FR9 | Epic 2 | 8-3 |\n    56в†’| FR13 | Epic 2 | 8-4 |\n    57в†’| FR4 | Epic 3 | 8-5 |\n    58в†’| FR12 | Epic 3 | 8-6 |\n    59в†’| FR5, FR6 | Epic 4 | 8-7 |\n    60в†’| FR10 | Epic 4 | 8-8 |\n    61в†’| FR11 | Epic 5 | 8-9 |\n    62в†’\n    63в†’## Epic List\n    64в†’\n    65в†’- **Epic 1: Rust Detection Foundation** вЂ” Stack detection, app type detection, state type expansion\n    66в†’- **Epic 2: Rust Coverage & Testing** вЂ” cargo-tarpaulin detection, report parsing, test output parsing\n    67в†’- **Epic 3: Rust Infrastructure** вЂ” Dockerfile template, verification Dockerfile\n    68в†’- **Epic 4: Rust Observability & Docs** вЂ” OTLP instrumentation, guidance doc, docs scaffolding\n    69в†’- **Epic 5: Rust Static Analysis** вЂ” Semgrep rules for tracing patterns\n    70в†’\n    71в†’## Epic 1: Rust Detection Foundation\n    72в†’\n    73в†’Enable codeharness to recognize Rust projects, detect their type, and store Rust-specific state.\n    74в†’\n    75в†’### Story 8-1: Rust stack and app type detection\n    76в†’\n    77в†’As a developer initializing codeharness on a Rust project,\n    78в†’I want the harness to detect my project as Rust and identify whether it's a CLI, server, library, or agent,\n    79в†’So that all downstream features (coverage, OTLP, Dockerfile) use the correct Rust configuration.\n    80в†’\n    81в†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    82в†’\n    83в†’**Given** a directory contains `Cargo.toml`\n    84в†’**When** `detectStack()` is called\n    85в†’**Then** it returns `'rust'`\n    86в†’\n    87в†’**Given** a Rust project with `[[bin]]` in Cargo.toml and no web framework deps\n    88в†’**When** `detectAppType()` is called\n    89в†’**Then** it returns `'cli'`\n    90в†’\n    91в†’**Given** a Rust project with `axum` in `[dependencies]`\n    92в†’**When** `detectAppType()` is called\n    93в†’**Then** it returns `'server'`\n    94в†’\n    95в†’**Given** a Rust project with `[lib]` section and no `[[bin]]`\n    96в†’**When** `detectAppType()` is called\n    97в†’**Then** it returns `'generic'` (library)\n    98в†’\n    99в†’**Given** a Rust project with `async-openai` in dependencies\n   100в†’**When** `detectAppType()` is called\n   101в†’**Then** it returns `'agent'`\n   102в†’\n   103в†’**Given** a Rust project with `[workspace]` in Cargo.toml\n   104в†’**When** `detectStack()` is called\n   105в†’**Then** it still returns `'rust'` (treated as single project)\n   106в†’\n   107в†’**Given** no `Cargo.toml` exists\n   108в†’**When** `detectStack()` is called\n   109в†’**Then** Rust is NOT detected (no false positive)\n   110в†’\n   111в†’### Story 8-2: Expand state types for Rust\n   112в†’\n   113в†’As a developer,\n   114в†’I want the harness state to support Rust-specific fields,\n   115в†’So that coverage tool and OTLP config are correctly stored.\n   116в†’\n   117в†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   118в†’\n   119в†’**Given** a Rust project is initialized\n   120в†’**When** state is written\n   121в†’**Then** `coverage.tool` accepts `'cargo-tarpaulin'` without type errors\n   122в†’\n   123в†’**Given** a Rust project has OTLP configured\n   124в†’**When** state is written\n   125в†’**Then** `otlp.rust_env_hint` field is present with value `'OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT'`\n   126в†’\n   127в†’## Epic 2: Rust Coverage & Testing\n   128в†’\n   129в†’Enable coverage detection, report parsing, and test output parsing for Rust projects using cargo-tarpaulin.\n   130в†’\n   131в†’### Story 8-3: cargo-tarpaulin coverage detection and parsing\n   132в†’\n   133в†’As a developer running coverage on a Rust project,\n   134в†’I want codeharness to detect cargo-tarpaulin, run it, and parse the JSON report,\n   135в†’So that coverage metrics are tracked at parity with Node.js/Python.\n   136в†’\n   137в†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   138в†’\n   139в†’**Given** a Rust project with `cargo-tarpaulin` installed\n   140в†’**When** `detectCoverageTool()` is called\n   141в†’**Then** it returns `{ tool: 'cargo-tarpaulin', runCommand: 'cargo tarpaulin --out json --output-dir coverage/', reportFormat: 'tarpaulin-json' }`\n   142в†’\n   143в†’**Given** a Rust workspace project\n   144в†’**When** `detectCoverageTool()` is called\n   145в†’**Then** the run command includes `--workspace` flag\n   146в†’\n   147в†’**Given** a `coverage/tarpaulin-report.json` file with `\"coverage\": 85.5`\n   148в†’**When** `parseCoverageReport()` is called with format `'tarpaulin-json'`\n   149в†’**Then** it returns `85.5`\n   150в†’\n   151в†’**Given** `cargo test` output containing `test result: ok. 42 passed; 3 failed; 0 ignored`\n   152в†’**When** `parseTestCounts()` is called\n   153в†’**Then** it returns `{ passCount: 42, failCount: 3 }`\n   154в†’\n   155в†’**Given** `cargo-tarpaulin` is NOT installed\n   156в†’**When** `detectCoverageTool()` is called on a Rust project\n   157в†’**Then** it returns `{ tool: 'unknown' }` with a warning\n   158в†’\n   159в†’### Story 8-4: Register cargo-tarpaulin in dependency registry\n   160в†’\n   161в†’As a developer initializing codeharness on a Rust project,\n   162в†’I want cargo-tarpaulin to be auto-installed if missing,\n   163в†’So that coverage works out of the box.\n   164в†’\n   165в†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   166в†’\n   167в†’**Given** `cargo-tarpaulin` is not installed\n   168в†’**When** `codeharness init` runs on a Rust project\n   169в†’**Then** it attempts `cargo install cargo-tarpaulin`\n   170в†’\n   171в†’**Given** the dependency registry\n   172в†’**When** checked for `cargo-tarpaulin`\n   173в†’**Then** it has `critical: false`, install command `cargo install cargo-tarpaulin`, check command `cargo tarpaulin --version`\n   174в†’\n   175в†’## Epic 3: Rust Infrastructure\n   176в†’\n   177в†’Generate Dockerfiles for Rust project deployment and verification.\n   178в†’\n   179в†’### Story 8-5: Rust Dockerfile template generation\n   180в†’\n   181в†’As a developer deploying a Rust project,\n   182в†’I want codeharness to generate a multi-stage Dockerfile,\n   183в†’So that I get a minimal runtime image with just the compiled binary.\n   184в†’\n   185в†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   186в†’\n   187в†’**Given** a Rust project without a Dockerfile\n   188в†’**When** `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called\n   189в†’**Then** it writes a multi-stage Dockerfile with `rust:1.82-slim` builder and `debian:bookworm-slim` runtime\n   190в†’\n   191в†’**Given** the generated Dockerfile\n   192в†’**When** inspected\n   193в†’**Then** it includes `cargo build --release` in build stage, `curl`/`jq` in runtime stage, and runs as non-root user\n   194в†’\n   195в†’**Given** a Rust project with an existing Dockerfile\n   196в†’**When** `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called\n   197в†’**Then** it returns `fail('Dockerfile already exists')`\n   198в†’\n   199в†’### Story 8-6: Rust verification Dockerfile\n   200в†’\n   201в†’As a developer verifying a Rust project,\n   202в†’I want a verification environment with Rust tooling, Semgrep, and showboat,\n   203в†’So that automated verification works for Rust projects.\n   204в†’\n   205в†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   206в†’\n   207в†’**Given** `templates/Dockerfile.verify.rust` exists\n   208в†’**When** built\n   209в†’**Then** it includes `rust:1.82-slim`, Python + Semgrep, showboat, cargo-tarpaulin, curl, jq\n   210в†’\n   211в†’**Given** the verification Dockerfile\n   212в†’**When** inspected\n   213в†’**Then** OTLP environment variables are configured pointing to host Docker endpoint\n   214в†’\n   215в†’## Epic 4: Rust Observability & Documentation\n   216в†’\n   217в†’Add OTLP instrumentation support and documentation scaffolding for Rust projects.\n   218в†’\n   219в†’### Story 8-7: Rust OTLP instrumentation\n   220в†’\n   221в†’As a developer instrumenting a Rust project,\n   222в†’I want codeharness to add OpenTelemetry crates and provide setup guidance,\n   223в†’So that I can quickly enable observability.\n   224в†’\n   225в†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   226в†’\n   227в†’**Given** a Rust project\n   228в†’**When** `instrumentProject()` runs\n   229в†’**Then** `cargo add opentelemetry opentelemetry-otlp tracing-opentelemetry tracing-subscriber` is executed\n   230в†’\n   231в†’**Given** OTLP instrumentation succeeds\n   232в†’**When** state is updated\n   233в†’**Then** `configureOtlpEnvVars()` writes `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` and `OTEL_SERVICE_NAME` to `.env.codeharness`\n   234в†’\n   235в†’**Given** a Rust project\n   236в†’**When** `configureAgent()` is called\n   237в†’**Then** it skips with info message (no standard Rust agent SDK yet)\n   238в†’\n   239в†’**Given** `templates/otlp/rust.md` exists\n   240в†’**When** read\n   241в†’**Then** it contains: packages to add, `tracing_subscriber` setup code snippet, `#[tracing::instrument]` usage, env vars, verification steps\n   242в†’\n   243в†’### Story 8-8: Rust documentation scaffolding\n   244в†’\n   245в†’As a developer initializing a Rust project,\n   246в†’I want AGENTS.md to include Rust-specific build/test commands,\n   247в†’So that AI agents know how to build and test my project.\n   248в†’\n   249в†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   250в†’\n   251в†’**Given** a Rust project\n   252в†’**When** `getStackLabel()` is called\n   253в†’**Then** it returns `'Rust (Cargo.toml)'`\n   254в†’\n   255в†’**Given** a Rust project\n   256в†’**When** `getCoverageTool()` is called\n   257в†’**Then** it returns `'cargo-tarpaulin'`\n   258в†’\n   259в†’**Given** a Rust project\n   260в†’**When** `generateAgentsMdContent()` is called\n   261в†’**Then** output includes `cargo build`, `cargo test`, `cargo tarpaulin --out json`\n   262в†’\n   263в†’**Given** a Rust project with `[package] name = \"myapp\"` in Cargo.toml\n   264в†’**When** `getProjectName()` is called\n   265в†’**Then** it returns `'myapp'` (reads from Cargo.toml, not package.json)\n   266в†’\n   267в†’## Epic 5: Rust Static Analysis\n   268в†’\n   269в†’Create Semgrep rules to detect observability gaps in Rust code using tracing crate patterns.\n   270в†’\n   271в†’### Story 8-9: Semgrep rules for Rust observability\n   272в†’\n   273в†’As a developer auditing a Rust project,\n   274в†’I want Semgrep to detect functions and error paths without tracing,\n   275в†’So that observability gaps are identified automatically.\n   276в†’\n   277в†’**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   278в†’\n   279в†’**Given** a Rust function without `tracing::debug!`, `tracing::info!`, or `#[instrument]`\n   280в†’**When** Semgrep runs with `rust-function-no-tracing` rule\n   281в†’**Then** it reports an observability gap\n   282в†’\n   283в†’**Given** a Rust `match` arm handling `Err` without `tracing::error!` or `tracing::warn!`\n   284в†’**When** Semgrep runs with `rust-catch-without-tracing` rule\n   285в†’**Then** it reports an observability gap\n   286в†’\n   287в†’**Given** a Rust `.map_err()` or `.unwrap_or_else()` closure without tracing macros\n   288в†’**When** Semgrep runs with `rust-error-path-no-tracing` rule\n   289в†’**Then** it reports an observability gap\n   290в†’\n   291в†’**Given** all 3 Rust rule files in `patches/observability/`\n   292в†’**When** `codeharness audit` runs on a Rust project with Semgrep installed\n   293в†’**Then** the observability static analysis dimension uses the Rust rules automatically (Semgrep auto-discovers by `languages: [rust]`)\n   294в†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01MpYJycPJfk2nBuCCAUW85g","session_id":"51b9d113-d480-4846-9e18-693f5f89566d","uuid":"697018de-ed62-4a84-9a13-6435aa430ba1","timestamp":"2026-03-23T07:08:49.488Z"}
