{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Lbw63YjUUQkQg4XHV2NbTn","type":"tool_result","content":"     1в†’/**\n     2в†’ * Verification prompt template for black-box verifier sessions.\n     3в†’ * Architecture Decision 6: All templates are TypeScript string literals.\n     4в†’ * Architecture Decision 10: Two-layer isolation вЂ” clean workspace + Docker container.\n     5в†’ *\n     6в†’ * This prompt is passed to `claude --print -p \"...\"` in a clean workspace\n     7в†’ * that contains NO source code. The verifier must exercise the feature\n     8в†’ * exclusively via `docker exec` and observability queries.\n     9в†’ */\n    10в†’\n    11в†’export type PromptProjectType = 'nodejs' | 'python' | 'plugin' | 'generic';\n    12в†’\n    13в†’export interface VerifyPromptConfig {\n    14в†’  /** Story key, e.g. \"13-3-black-box-verifier-agent\" */\n    15в†’  storyKey: string;\n    16в†’  /** Full content of story.md from the clean workspace */\n    17в†’  storyContent: string;\n    18в†’  /** Docker container name (default: \"codeharness-verify\") */\n    19в†’  containerName?: string;\n    20в†’  /** Project type for verification strategy guidance */\n    21в†’  projectType?: PromptProjectType;\n    22в†’  /** Observability endpoint overrides */\n    23в†’  observabilityEndpoints?: {\n    24в†’    victoriaLogs?: string;\n    25в†’    victoriaMetrics?: string;\n    26в†’    victoriaTraces?: string;\n    27в†’  };\n    28в†’}\n    29в†’\n    30в†’const DEFAULT_CONTAINER = 'codeharness-verify';\n    31в†’\n    32в†’const DEFAULT_ENDPOINTS = {\n    33в†’  victoriaLogs: 'http://localhost:9428',\n    34в†’  victoriaMetrics: 'http://localhost:8428',\n    35в†’  victoriaTraces: 'http://localhost:16686',\n    36в†’};\n    37в†’\n    38в†’/** Returns project-type-specific verification guidance. */\n    39в†’export function projectTypeGuidance(projectType: PromptProjectType, container: string): string {\n    40в†’  switch (projectType) {\n    41в†’    case 'nodejs':\n    42в†’    case 'python':\n    43в†’      return `### Project Type: ${projectType === 'nodejs' ? 'Node.js CLI' : 'Python CLI'}\n    44в†’\n    45в†’Execute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n    46в†’- \\`docker exec ${container} <cli-command> [args]\\`\n    47в†’- Capture exit codes: \\`docker exec ${container} sh -c '<command>; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'\\`\n    48в†’- For ${projectType === 'nodejs' ? 'Node.js' : 'Python'} projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.`;\n    49в†’\n    50в†’    case 'plugin':\n    51в†’      return `### Project Type: Claude Code Plugin\n    52в†’\n    53в†’This is a Claude Code plugin project. Verify using \\`claude --print\\` inside the container:\n    54в†’- \\`docker exec ${container} claude --print -p \"<prompt>\" --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit --max-budget-usd 1\\`\n    55в†’- Plugin commands and hooks are installed in the container's Claude Code environment.\n    56в†’- Test slash commands by prompting Claude to run them inside the container.`;\n    57в†’\n    58в†’    case 'generic':\n    59в†’      return `### Project Type: Unknown / Generic\n    60в†’\n    61в†’The project stack was not recognized. Adapt your verification approach to the tools available:\n    62в†’- Use basic CLI tools: \\`bash\\`, \\`curl\\`, \\`jq\\`, \\`node\\`\n    63в†’- Inspect any artifacts copied into the container\n    64в†’- If the project provides a CLI binary, test it directly\n    65в†’- Adapt to whatever tools and artifacts are available вЂ” do not refuse verification`;\n    66в†’  }\n    67в†’}\n    68в†’\n    69в†’/**\n    70в†’ * Generates the verification prompt for a black-box verifier session.\n    71в†’ * The prompt instructs the verifier to:\n    72в†’ * - Read README.md for usage guidance\n    73в†’ * - Run ALL commands via `docker exec`\n    74в†’ * - Query observability endpoints for runtime evidence\n    75в†’ * - Write a proof document at `verification/{storyKey}-proof.md`\n    76в†’ * - Report REAL failures вЂ” never fabricate evidence\n    77в†’ */\n    78в†’export function verifyPromptTemplate(config: VerifyPromptConfig): string {\n    79в†’  const container = config.containerName ?? DEFAULT_CONTAINER;\n    80в†’  const projectType = config.projectType ?? 'nodejs';\n    81в†’  const endpoints = {\n    82в†’    ...DEFAULT_ENDPOINTS,\n    83в†’    ...config.observabilityEndpoints,\n    84в†’  };\n    85в†’\n    86в†’  return `You are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective вЂ” using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n    87в†’\n    88в†’## Why Black-Box Verification\n    89в†’\n    90в†’This workspace contains NO source code. The \\`src/\\` directory does not exist. This is intentional вЂ” you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n    91в†’\n    92в†’## Step 1: Read README.md\n    93в†’\n    94в†’Start by reading \\`README.md\\` in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n    95в†’\n    96в†’## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n    97в†’\n    98в†’The story file \\`story.md\\` contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Here is its content:\n    99в†’\n   100в†’---\n   101в†’${config.storyContent}\n   102в†’---\n   103в†’\n   104в†’## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n   105в†’\n   106в†’For EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n   107в†’\n   108в†’1. Run commands inside the Docker container via \\`docker exec ${container} ...\\`\n   109в†’2. Capture the command output as evidence\n   110в†’3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n   111в†’4. For ACs that involve Claude Code sessions or agent workflows, use \\`docker exec ${container} claude ...\\` to spawn real sessions inside the container\n   112в†’\n   113в†’### Docker Container\n   114в†’\n   115в†’- Container name: \\`${container}\\`\n   116в†’- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: \\`docker exec ${container} <command>\\`\n   117в†’- Example: \\`docker exec ${container} codeharness --version\\`\n   118в†’- Example: \\`docker exec ${container} codeharness init --json\\`\n   119в†’- Example: \\`docker exec ${container} claude --print --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"Run /harness-run\" --max-budget-usd 1\\`\n   120в†’\n   121в†’The container has the following tools installed:\n   122в†’- \\`codeharness\\` вЂ” the project CLI\n   123в†’- \\`claude\\` вЂ” Claude Code CLI (authenticated via ANTHROPIC_API_KEY env var)\n   124в†’- \\`curl\\`, \\`jq\\` вЂ” for querying observability endpoints\n   125в†’- \\`showboat\\` вЂ” for proof document validation\n   126в†’- \\`node\\`, \\`npm\\` вЂ” Node.js runtime\n   127в†’\n   128в†’**IMPORTANT: When invoking \\`claude --print\\` inside Docker, always pass \\`--allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit\\` to prevent the nested session from hanging on tool permission prompts.**\n   129в†’\n   130в†’${projectTypeGuidance(projectType, container)}\n   131в†’\n   132в†’### Observability Endpoints\n   133в†’\n   134в†’Query these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n   135в†’\n   136в†’- **VictoriaLogs** (logs): \\`${endpoints.victoriaLogs}\\`\n   137в†’  - Example: \\`curl '${endpoints.victoriaLogs}/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&limit=10'\\`\n   138в†’- **VictoriaMetrics** (metrics): \\`${endpoints.victoriaMetrics}\\`\n   139в†’  - Example: \\`curl '${endpoints.victoriaMetrics}/api/v1/query?query=up'\\`\n   140в†’- **VictoriaTraces** (traces): \\`${endpoints.victoriaTraces}\\`\n   141в†’  - Example: \\`curl '${endpoints.victoriaTraces}/api/traces?service=codeharness-verify&limit=10'\\`\n   142в†’\n   143в†’## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n   144в†’\n   145в†’After EACH \\`docker exec\\` command you run, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n   146в†’\n   147в†’\\`\\`\\`bash\n   148в†’curl '${endpoints.victoriaLogs}/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n   149в†’\\`\\`\\`\n   150в†’\n   151в†’- If the response contains **one or more log entries**, the code path has observability coverage. Note the count in your proof.\n   152в†’- If the response contains **zero log entries**, the code path is a silent gap. Include this tag in the AC section of your proof:\n   153в†’\n   154в†’  \\`[OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction\\`\n   155в†’\n   156в†’This check detects silent code paths вЂ” places where the application runs but produces no telemetry. Every AC should produce some log output when exercised.\n   157в†’\n   158в†’## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n   159в†’\n   160в†’Write your verification proof to: \\`verification/${config.storyKey}-proof.md\\`\n   161в†’\n   162в†’Use this format for each AC:\n   163в†’\n   164в†’\\`\\`\\`markdown\n   165в†’## AC N: <description>\n   166в†’\n   167в†’\\`\\`\\`bash\n   168в†’docker exec ${container} <command>\n   169в†’\\`\\`\\`\n   170в†’\n   171в†’\\`\\`\\`output\n   172в†’<actual output>\n   173в†’\\`\\`\\`\n   174в†’\\`\\`\\`\n   175в†’\n   176в†’**IMPORTANT: Only use \\`bash\\` and \\`output\\` as code fence languages.** Never use bare \\`\\`\\` fences without a language tag. If quoting code snippets, use \\`\\`\\`text. Showboat will try to execute any unlabeled code block.\n   177в†’\n   178в†’## Critical Rules\n   179в†’\n   180в†’1. **ALL commands MUST use \\`docker exec ${container} ...\\`** вЂ” do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n   181в†’2. **Do NOT attempt to access source code** вЂ” there is no \\`src/\\` directory in this workspace. If you try to \\`grep\\`, \\`cat\\`, or \\`find\\` source files, you will find nothing.\n   182в†’3. **Report REAL failures** вЂ” if a feature does not work via the CLI or the documentation is insufficient to exercise it, report that as a verification failure with specific details about what went wrong. Do NOT fabricate passing evidence.\n   183в†’4. **Every AC needs functional evidence** вЂ” reading docs alone is not evidence. You must execute commands and capture output.\n   184в†’5. **Verify aggressively, escalate narrowly.** If an AC has 5 parts and you can verify 4, verify those 4 and escalate ONLY the specific part you cannot reach. Never blanket-escalate an entire AC because one aspect requires something unavailable.\n   185в†’6. **[ESCALATE] is ONLY for things that are genuinely impossible to automate** вЂ” physical hardware, paid external services, human visual judgment. Infrastructure problems (missing binary, wrong version, tree-shaking, Docker config) are NOT valid escalation reasons. If a tool is missing from the container, that is a bug to report as [FAIL], not an [ESCALATE]. The harness will fix the infrastructure and re-verify.\n   186в†’7. **\\`claude\\` CLI is available** inside the container. If an AC requires spawning a Claude Code session, running a slash command, or testing agent behavior, use \\`docker exec ${container} claude --print --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"...\" --max-budget-usd 1\\` to actually test it. Do NOT escalate just because \"it needs a Claude session.\"\n   187в†’8. **Never switch to unit-testable verification.** If Docker verification doesn't work, report WHY as a [FAIL] вЂ” don't fall back to running tests on the host. The harness-run flow will fix the Docker problem and retry.\n   188в†’`;\n   189в†’}\n   190в†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"51b9d113-d480-4846-9e18-693f5f89566d","uuid":"92d4d5a9-0430-4c1a-bf91-eeabe7e734c9","timestamp":"2026-03-23T07:20:32.781Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/templates/verify-prompt.ts","content":"/**\n * Verification prompt template for black-box verifier sessions.\n * Architecture Decision 6: All templates are TypeScript string literals.\n * Architecture Decision 10: Two-layer isolation вЂ” clean workspace + Docker container.\n *\n * This prompt is passed to `claude --print -p \"...\"` in a clean workspace\n * that contains NO source code. The verifier must exercise the feature\n * exclusively via `docker exec` and observability queries.\n */\n\nexport type PromptProjectType = 'nodejs' | 'python' | 'plugin' | 'generic';\n\nexport interface VerifyPromptConfig {\n  /** Story key, e.g. \"13-3-black-box-verifier-agent\" */\n  storyKey: string;\n  /** Full content of story.md from the clean workspace */\n  storyContent: string;\n  /** Docker container name (default: \"codeharness-verify\") */\n  containerName?: string;\n  /** Project type for verification strategy guidance */\n  projectType?: PromptProjectType;\n  /** Observability endpoint overrides */\n  observabilityEndpoints?: {\n    victoriaLogs?: string;\n    victoriaMetrics?: string;\n    victoriaTraces?: string;\n  };\n}\n\nconst DEFAULT_CONTAINER = 'codeharness-verify';\n\nconst DEFAULT_ENDPOINTS = {\n  victoriaLogs: 'http://localhost:9428',\n  victoriaMetrics: 'http://localhost:8428',\n  victoriaTraces: 'http://localhost:16686',\n};\n\n/** Returns project-type-specific verification guidance. */\nexport function projectTypeGuidance(projectType: PromptProjectType, container: string): string {\n  switch (projectType) {\n    case 'nodejs':\n    case 'python':\n      return `### Project Type: ${projectType === 'nodejs' ? 'Node.js CLI' : 'Python CLI'}\n\nExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n- \\`docker exec ${container} <cli-command> [args]\\`\n- Capture exit codes: \\`docker exec ${container} sh -c '<command>; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'\\`\n- For ${projectType === 'nodejs' ? 'Node.js' : 'Python'} projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.`;\n\n    case 'plugin':\n      return `### Project Type: Claude Code Plugin\n\nThis is a Claude Code plugin project. Verify using \\`claude --print\\` inside the container:\n- \\`docker exec ${container} claude --print -p \"<prompt>\" --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit --max-budget-usd 1\\`\n- Plugin commands and hooks are installed in the container's Claude Code environment.\n- Test slash commands by prompting Claude to run them inside the container.`;\n\n    case 'generic':\n      return `### Project Type: Unknown / Generic\n\nThe project stack was not recognized. Adapt your verification approach to the tools available:\n- Use basic CLI tools: \\`bash\\`, \\`curl\\`, \\`jq\\`, \\`node\\`\n- Inspect any artifacts copied into the container\n- If the project provides a CLI binary, test it directly\n- Adapt to whatever tools and artifacts are available вЂ” do not refuse verification`;\n  }\n}\n\n/**\n * Generates the verification prompt for a black-box verifier session.\n * The prompt instructs the verifier to:\n * - Read README.md for usage guidance\n * - Run ALL commands via `docker exec`\n * - Query observability endpoints for runtime evidence\n * - Write a proof document at `verification/{storyKey}-proof.md`\n * - Report REAL failures вЂ” never fabricate evidence\n */\nexport function verifyPromptTemplate(config: VerifyPromptConfig): string {\n  const container = config.containerName ?? DEFAULT_CONTAINER;\n  const projectType = config.projectType ?? 'nodejs';\n  const endpoints = {\n    ...DEFAULT_ENDPOINTS,\n    ...config.observabilityEndpoints,\n  };\n\n  return `You are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective вЂ” using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The \\`src/\\` directory does not exist. This is intentional вЂ” you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading \\`README.md\\` in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story file \\`story.md\\` contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Here is its content:\n\n---\n${config.storyContent}\n---\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via \\`docker exec ${container} ...\\`\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n4. For ACs that involve Claude Code sessions or agent workflows, use \\`docker exec ${container} claude ...\\` to spawn real sessions inside the container\n\n### Docker Container\n\n- Container name: \\`${container}\\`\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: \\`docker exec ${container} <command>\\`\n- Example: \\`docker exec ${container} codeharness --version\\`\n- Example: \\`docker exec ${container} codeharness init --json\\`\n- Example: \\`docker exec ${container} claude --print --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"Run /harness-run\" --max-budget-usd 1\\`\n\nThe container has the following tools installed:\n- \\`codeharness\\` вЂ” the project CLI\n- \\`claude\\` вЂ” Claude Code CLI (authenticated via ANTHROPIC_API_KEY env var)\n- \\`curl\\`, \\`jq\\` вЂ” for querying observability endpoints\n- \\`showboat\\` вЂ” for proof document validation\n- \\`node\\`, \\`npm\\` вЂ” Node.js runtime\n\n**IMPORTANT: When invoking \\`claude --print\\` inside Docker, always pass \\`--allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit\\` to prevent the nested session from hanging on tool permission prompts.**\n\n${projectTypeGuidance(projectType, container)}\n\n### Observability Endpoints\n\nQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n\n- **VictoriaLogs** (logs): \\`${endpoints.victoriaLogs}\\`\n  - Example: \\`curl '${endpoints.victoriaLogs}/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&limit=10'\\`\n- **VictoriaMetrics** (metrics): \\`${endpoints.victoriaMetrics}\\`\n  - Example: \\`curl '${endpoints.victoriaMetrics}/api/v1/query?query=up'\\`\n- **VictoriaTraces** (traces): \\`${endpoints.victoriaTraces}\\`\n  - Example: \\`curl '${endpoints.victoriaTraces}/api/traces?service=codeharness-verify&limit=10'\\`\n\n## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n\nAfter EACH \\`docker exec\\` command you run, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\ncurl '${endpoints.victoriaLogs}/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n- If the response contains **one or more log entries**, the code path has observability coverage. Note the count in your proof.\n- If the response contains **zero log entries**, the code path is a silent gap. Include this tag in the AC section of your proof:\n\n  \\`[OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction\\`\n\nThis check detects silent code paths вЂ” places where the application runs but produces no telemetry. Every AC should produce some log output when exercised.\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: \\`verification/${config.storyKey}-proof.md\\`\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n\n\\`\\`\\`markdown\n## AC N: <description>\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\ndocker exec ${container} <command>\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n\\`\\`\\`output\n<actual output>\n\\`\\`\\`\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**IMPORTANT: Only use \\`bash\\` and \\`output\\` as code fence languages.** Never use bare \\`\\`\\` fences without a language tag. If quoting code snippets, use \\`\\`\\`text. Showboat will try to execute any unlabeled code block.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. **ALL commands MUST use \\`docker exec ${container} ...\\`** вЂ” do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n2. **Do NOT attempt to access source code** вЂ” there is no \\`src/\\` directory in this workspace. If you try to \\`grep\\`, \\`cat\\`, or \\`find\\` source files, you will find nothing.\n3. **Report REAL failures** вЂ” if a feature does not work via the CLI or the documentation is insufficient to exercise it, report that as a verification failure with specific details about what went wrong. Do NOT fabricate passing evidence.\n4. **Every AC needs functional evidence** вЂ” reading docs alone is not evidence. You must execute commands and capture output.\n5. **Verify aggressively, escalate narrowly.** If an AC has 5 parts and you can verify 4, verify those 4 and escalate ONLY the specific part you cannot reach. Never blanket-escalate an entire AC because one aspect requires something unavailable.\n6. **[ESCALATE] is ONLY for things that are genuinely impossible to automate** вЂ” physical hardware, paid external services, human visual judgment. Infrastructure problems (missing binary, wrong version, tree-shaking, Docker config) are NOT valid escalation reasons. If a tool is missing from the container, that is a bug to report as [FAIL], not an [ESCALATE]. The harness will fix the infrastructure and re-verify.\n7. **\\`claude\\` CLI is available** inside the container. If an AC requires spawning a Claude Code session, running a slash command, or testing agent behavior, use \\`docker exec ${container} claude --print --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"...\" --max-budget-usd 1\\` to actually test it. Do NOT escalate just because \"it needs a Claude session.\"\n8. **Never switch to unit-testable verification.** If Docker verification doesn't work, report WHY as a [FAIL] вЂ” don't fall back to running tests on the host. The harness-run flow will fix the Docker problem and retry.\n`;\n}\n","numLines":190,"startLine":1,"totalLines":190}}}
